<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="prep-11-2">
  <title>Resources for 11/2</title>

  <objectives>
    <introduction>
      <p>For the content of this class, you will be expected to be able to do the following:</p>
    </introduction>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Use the above properties to solve applied problems involving exponential functions.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Apply your understanding of exponential and logarithm functions to solve problems similar to half-life problems for exponential decay.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Apply your understanding of exponential and logarithm functions to solve problems similar to doubling time problems for exponential growth.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <subsection xml:id="video-activity-logarithm-applications-2">
    <title>Video &amp; Activities for Applications of Logarithms (Continued from Last Class)</title>
    <p>
      Below is a YouTube video on <em>applications of logarithms</em>. It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.
    </p>

    <video youtube="xawMyQexzKs" />

    <example>
      <title>Logarithm Applications</title>
      <p>
        For the following, justify any formulas you use that are not covered in class.
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              You invest $400 in an account that earns 4% interest annually.  How long does it take for your account to be $1000?
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              When you inject a certain drug, it takes 25 hours for the concentration of the drug in the bloodstream to decrease by half.  How long does it take for the concentration to decrease to 10% of its initial concentration?
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </example>
    <p>
      Feel free to post any questions you have on the <url href="">FigJam board</url> for the next class.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="video-activity-half-life">
    <title>Video &amp; Activities for Half-Life and Related Problems</title>
    <p>
      Below is a YouTube video on problems related to the concept of <em>half-life</em>. It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.
    </p>

    <video youtube="qX4VWiDr4Sw" />

    <example>
      <title>Half-Life and Related Problems</title>
      <p>
        For the following, justify any formulas you use that are not covered in class.
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              An account with a fixed annual interest rate takes 25 years to triple in value.
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    How long does it take for the account to double in value?
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    What is the annual interest rate?
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              A radioactive material decays 30% in 5 years.
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    What percent of the material decays after 12 years?
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    What percent of the material decays each year?
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    How long will it take for 95% of the material to decay?
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </example>
    <p>
      Feel free to post any questions you have on the <url href="">FigJam board</url> for the next class.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Optional Reading</title>
    <p>
      Section 3.5: pp. 192-198
    </p>
    <p>
      Here is a link for the <url href="https://activecalculus.org/prelude/sec-exp-log-properties.html">HTML version of Section 3.5</url>.
    </p>
  </subsection>
</section>